<subSubSection pageId="47" pageNumber="48" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph blockId="47.[151,1437,1618,2003]" pageId="47" pageNumber="48">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,321,1726,1751]" pageId="47" pageNumber="48">Diagnosis.</emphasis>
Belongs to the 
<taxonomicName box="[501,696,1726,1751]" class="Insecta" family="Nepticulidae" genus="Stigmella" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="47" pageNumber="48" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="pseudodigitata">
<emphasis box="[501,696,1726,1751]" italics="true" pageId="47" pageNumber="48">S. pseudodigitata</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
species group. The combination of blue and purple scales on the forewing, closely juxtaposed caudal processes of gnathos, and specific set of cornuti distinguishes 
<taxonomicName box="[1276,1394,1762,1787]" class="Insecta" family="Nepticulidae" genus="Stigmella" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="47" pageNumber="48" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="azulella" status="sp. nov.">
<emphasis box="[1276,1394,1762,1787]" italics="true" pageId="47" pageNumber="48">S. azulella</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<emphasis bold="true" pageId="47" pageNumber="48">
<taxonomicNameLabel pageId="47" pageNumber="48" rank="species">sp. nov.</taxonomicNameLabel>
</emphasis>
from all other 
<taxonomicName box="[368,473,1798,1823]" class="Insecta" family="Nepticulidae" genus="Stigmella" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="47" pageNumber="48" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[368,473,1798,1823]" italics="true" pageId="47" pageNumber="48">Stigmella</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
species, including the most similar and probably closely related 
<taxonomicName box="[1198,1392,1798,1823]" class="Insecta" family="Nepticulidae" genus="Stigmella" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="47" pageNumber="48" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="pseudodigitata">
<emphasis box="[1198,1212,1799,1822]" italics="true" pageId="47" pageNumber="48">S</emphasis>
. 
<emphasis box="[1226,1392,1798,1823]" italics="true" pageId="47" pageNumber="48">pseudodigitata</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection lastPageId="48" lastPageNumber="49" pageId="47" pageNumber="48" type="description">
<paragraph blockId="47.[151,1437,1618,2003]" lastBlockId="48.[151,1437,151,752]" lastPageId="48" lastPageNumber="49" pageId="47" pageNumber="48">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,260,1834,1859]" pageId="47" pageNumber="48">Male</emphasis>
(
<figureCitation box="[275,359,1834,1859]" captionStart="FIGURE 32" captionStartId="12.[151,250,1881,1903]" captionTargetBox="[161,1404,218,1850]" captionTargetId="figure@12.[157,1429,195,1859]" captionTargetPageId="12" captionText="FIGURE 32. Adults of the central Andean Nepticulidae." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/557162/files/figure.png" pageId="47" pageNumber="48">Fig. 32</figureCitation>
). Forewing length about 
<quantity box="[638,727,1835,1859]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="2.1" pageId="47" pageNumber="48" unit="mm" value="2.1">2.1 mm</quantity>
; wingspan about 
<quantity box="[921,1010,1834,1859]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="4.6" pageId="47" pageNumber="48" unit="mm" value="4.6">4.6 mm</quantity>
. Head: palpi pale ochre cream; frontal tuft dark ferruginous; collar and scape golden cream to ochre cream; antenna slightly longer than half the length of forewing; flagellum with 24–26, dark brown to grey with some golden gloss and blue iridescence. Thorax, tegula, forewing and its fringe concolorous, pale brownish grey with strong blue and little purple iridescence (on certain angle of view forewing may look ferruginous with a fuscous apical spot); underside of forewing dark grey, without spots. Hindwing and its fringe pale brownish grey on upper side and underside, with golden gloss but without spots or blue iridescence. Legs dark grey-brown on upper side, grey on underside. Abdomen fuscous grey, metallic glossy on upper side, grey on underside; anal tufts grey cream to cream; genital plates yellowish cream.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="48.[151,1437,151,752]" box="[199,418,260,285]" pageId="48" pageNumber="49">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,286,260,285]" pageId="48" pageNumber="49">Female</emphasis>
. Unknown.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="48.[151,1437,151,752]" pageId="48" pageNumber="49">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,375,295,320]" pageId="48" pageNumber="49">Male genitalia</emphasis>
(
<figureCitation box="[395,533,295,320]" captionStart="FIGURES 92 – 94" captionStartId="49.[151,264,1949,1972]" captionTargetBox="[165,1426,194,1922]" captionTargetId="figure@49.[153,1433,193,1929]" captionTargetPageId="49" captionText="FIGURES 92 – 94. Male genitalia of Stigmella azulella Diškus &amp; Stonis, sp. nov. 92, 93, capsule, holotype, genitalia slide no. AD 666; 94, same, phallus (ZMUC)." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/557178/files/figure.png" pageId="48" pageNumber="49">Figs 92–94</figureCitation>
). Capsule longer (225 µm) than wide (155 µm). Uncus truncated (
<figureCitation box="[1334,1424,295,320]" captionStart="FIGURES 97 – 98" captionStartId="52.[151,264,1937,1960]" captionTargetBox="[153,1431,203,1915]" captionTargetId="figure@52.[153,1433,193,1916]" captionTargetPageId="52" captionText="FIGURES 97 – 98. Male genitalia of Acalyptris murex Diškus &amp; Stonis, sp. nov., holotype, genitalia slide no. AD 850 (ZMUC). 97, details of capsule; 98, phallus." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/557181/files/figure.png" pageId="48" pageNumber="49">Fig. 97</figureCitation>
). Gnathos with two closely juxtaposed caudal processes. Valva (
<figureCitation box="[848,975,332,357]" captionStart="FIGURES 97 – 98" captionStartId="52.[151,264,1937,1960]" captionTargetBox="[153,1431,203,1915]" captionTargetId="figure@52.[153,1433,193,1916]" captionTargetPageId="52" captionText="FIGURES 97 – 98. Male genitalia of Acalyptris murex Diškus &amp; Stonis, sp. nov., holotype, genitalia slide no. AD 850 (ZMUC). 97, details of capsule; 98, phallus." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/557181/files/figure.png" pageId="48" pageNumber="49">Figs 97, 98</figureCitation>
) 110–115 µm long, 45–50 µm wide, with very long apical process and slightly bulged inner lobe; transtilla with corners extended into very short sublateral processes (
<figureCitation box="[273,357,404,429]" captionStart="FIGURES 92 – 94" captionStartId="49.[151,264,1949,1972]" captionTargetBox="[165,1426,194,1922]" captionTargetId="figure@49.[153,1433,193,1929]" captionTargetPageId="49" captionText="FIGURES 92 – 94. Male genitalia of Stigmella azulella Diškus &amp; Stonis, sp. nov. 92, 93, capsule, holotype, genitalia slide no. AD 666; 94, same, phallus (ZMUC)." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/557178/files/figure.png" pageId="48" pageNumber="49">Fig. 92</figureCitation>
). Vinculum with short ventral plate and pointed lateral lobes. Phallus (
<figureCitation box="[1143,1224,404,429]" captionStart="FIGURES 92 – 94" captionStartId="49.[151,264,1949,1972]" captionTargetBox="[165,1426,194,1922]" captionTargetId="figure@49.[153,1433,193,1929]" captionTargetPageId="49" captionText="FIGURES 92 – 94. Male genitalia of Stigmella azulella Diškus &amp; Stonis, sp. nov. 92, 93, capsule, holotype, genitalia slide no. AD 666; 94, same, phallus (ZMUC)." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/557178/files/figure.png" pageId="48" pageNumber="49">Fig. 94</figureCitation>
) 230 µm long, 60– 75 µm wide; vesica with a specific set of cornuti comprised of one large, faceted cornutus, four wide spine-like cornuti and three long digitate cornuti.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="48.[151,1437,151,752]" pageId="48" pageNumber="49">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,323,511,536]" pageId="48" pageNumber="49">Bionomics</emphasis>
. Host-plant unknown (remains unidentified). Larvae mine in leaves in April. Leaf-mine as a very long and narrow gallery along the leaf margin. Cocoon orangish beige, almost round; length about 
<quantity box="[1271,1360,548,573]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="2.5" pageId="48" pageNumber="49" unit="mm" value="2.5">2.5 mm</quantity>
, width about 
<quantity box="[220,309,583,608]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.5" pageId="48" pageNumber="49" unit="mm" value="1.5">1.5 mm</quantity>
. Adults fly in May.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="48" pageNumber="49" type="distribution">
<paragraph blockId="48.[151,1437,151,752]" pageId="48" pageNumber="49">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,345,620,645]" pageId="48" pageNumber="49">Distribution</emphasis>
(
<figureCitation box="[364,442,620,645]" captionStart="FIGURES 9 – 11" captionStartId="6.[151,264,1932,1955]" captionTargetBox="[172,1411,209,1896]" captionTargetId="figure@6.[153,1433,193,1911]" captionTargetPageId="6" captionText="FIGURES 9 – 11. Distribution of the central Andean Nepticulidae. 9, species recorded at altitudes below 3700 m; 10, 11, some collecting areas in Peru. * — Stigmella epicosma Meyrick is also known from Arica Province, northern Chile (Vargas 2011); ** – S. inca sp. nov. is also discovered in southern Ecuador." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/557158/files/figure.png" pageId="48" pageNumber="49">Figs 9</figureCitation>
). This species occurs in the Bolivian Andes (
<collectingCountry box="[984,1072,620,645]" name="Bolivia" pageId="48" pageNumber="49">Bolivia</collectingCountry>
: Nor Yungas Departamento) at altitudes about 
<quantity box="[322,407,656,680]" metricMagnitude="3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="2.03" pageId="48" pageNumber="49" unit="m" value="2030.0">2030 m</quantity>
(
<figureCitation box="[422,552,655,680]" captionStart="FIGURES 19 – 28" captionStartId="8.[151,264,1786,1809]" captionTargetBox="[151,1435,194,1764]" captionTargetId="figure@8.[150,1436,193,1765]" captionTargetPageId="8" captionText="FIGURES 19 – 28. Distribution of some central Andean Nepticulidae. 19 – 28, habitats, Bolivia." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/557160/files/figure.png" pageId="48" pageNumber="49">Figs 25–28</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="48" pageNumber="49" type="etymology">
<paragraph blockId="48.[151,1437,151,752]" pageId="48" pageNumber="49">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,334,692,717]" pageId="48" pageNumber="49">Etymology.</emphasis>
The species name is derived from Spanish 
<emphasis box="[815,861,692,717]" italics="true" pageId="48" pageNumber="49">azul</emphasis>
(blue) in reference to the numerous distinctive blue and purple scales on the male forewing.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
